What we actually built — explained simply
We built a 3-agent fraud detection system. Here's what each agent did:

Agent 1 — Heuristic Scanner (free, no LLM) Scanned every transaction using rules like: is this withdrawal happening in a country the user has never been to? Is this amount 4x their normal spending? Is it 2am? This flagged the obvious stuff instantly at zero cost.

Agent 2 — LLM Reasoning Agent (gpt-4o-mini) Took the suspicious transactions from Agent 1 and sent them to an LLM with full user context — salary, job, home city, normal spending patterns. The LLM then reasoned about whether each one was actually fraud or just unusual.

Agent 3 — Ensemble Decision Agent Combined both signals. If the LLM confirmed it OR the heuristic score was extremely high, it went into the final fraud list.

The key insight we discovered from the data: The clearest fraud signal was geographic impossibility — someone living in Italy withdrawing from ATMs in Mississippi, Pakistan, Brazil, and Indonesia on the same day. That's physically impossible and the scoring system rewarded catching those heavily.

